- UNDERSTANDING DOCKERFILE 
    - Dockerfile is a series of instructions on how to build the docker image, each instruction  creates a layer in the image which makes it easy to track changes and optimise builds
    sort of like a recipe for creating your containerized application providing step by step instructions on how to create a image, this means that you can re create the exact sdame 
    enviroment every single time.
    - 5 KEY COMMANDS
        - The FROM instruction is the foundation of a Dockerfile. It defines the base image that your application will be built on, meaning it provides the operating system 
        and required tools to run your app. For example, if you write FROM node:18, Docker will use a prebuilt image that already includes Node.js version 18 installed. 
        This is important because everything in your container is built on top of this starting point, so without FROM, the Dockerfile would not know what environment to 
        use.
        - The WORKDIR instruction sets the working directory inside the container. It is like choosing a folder where all your application files and commands will run. 
        For example, WORKDIR /app creates or moves into a folder called /app inside the container. After this is set, every command that follows will run inside this 
        folder, which keeps the container organised and avoids everything being placed in the root directory.
        - The COPY instruction is used to copy files from your local machine into the container. For example, COPY . . copies everything from your current project folder 
        into the container’s working directory. A more efficient example is COPY package.json ., which only copies the package.json file. This is useful because it allows 
        Docker to use caching more effectively and avoid repeating unnecessary steps when only your code changes.
        - The RUN instruction is used to execute commands while the image is being built. It is mainly used to install dependencies or set up the environment. For example, 
        RUN npm install installs all the dependencies listed in your package.json file. This step only happens during the image build process, not when the container is 
        running, which is an important difference compared to CMD.
        - The CMD instruction defines what should happen when the container starts. It is the command that launches your application. For example, CMD ["node", "app.js"] 
        tells Docker to run the Node.js application using the app.js file when the container starts. Only one CMD is used in a Dockerfile, and if there are multiple, the 
        last one will override the others.
        - Order is very important in a Dockerfile because Docker builds images in layers and caches each step to improve performance. For example, a bad approach would be 
        COPY . . followed by RUN npm install, because any change in your code would force Docker to reinstall everything again, which is slow. A better approach is COPY 
        package.json . followed by RUN npm install, and then COPY . ., because package.json changes less often, allowing Docker to reuse cached layers and speed up the 
        build process.
        - When Docker builds an image, it follows each step in order. For example, in a Dockerfile with FROM node:18, WORKDIR /app, COPY package.json ., RUN npm install, 
        \COPY . ., and CMD ["node", "app.js"], Docker will first load the Node.js base image, then create the /app folder, copy the package file, install dependencies, 
        copy the rest of the project files, and finally set the command that runs the application. Each of these steps becomes a layer in the final image.
        - Common mistakes in Dockerfiles include placing CMD in the middle instead of at the end, copying all files too early which breaks caching, not using WORKDIR which 
        leads to messy file paths, and confusing RUN with CMD. For example, RUN npm install is used during the build process to install dependencies, while CMD ["node", "app.js"] is 
        used at runtime to start the application.
        - A simple way to remember Dockerfile structure is to think of it as a sequence: base image, working folder, files, setup, then run. In other words, Dockerfiles follow 
        the logic of building an environment step by step until the application is ready to start.

